  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime provides guidelines for member states to prevent money laundering.\n\n3. The Palermo Convention and the Merida Convention also address money laundering as part of broader anti-crime efforts.\n\n4. Most countries have domestic laws that implement international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar legislation in the European Union.\n\n5. Many countries require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs\n\nThese laws require international cooperation and information sharing to effectively combat money laundering across borders.",
